After a while trying to figure out why jquery was failing with error `Object doesn't support property or method 'remove'` in IE8 during initialization, I found out that it was a matter of it using the wrong function (jquery.fn.detach instead of detach() on the current scope), which in turn was due to "use strict" being added to jquery 1.11.3 and `this` being replaced with `undefined`.

After upgrading the versions of babelify and browserify and making the correct adjustments, I found out that I still had the issue. 

In the end, it appears that the mere fact of using `bundler.add()` in my gulp task is triggering a different way of bundling the assets, which adds "use strict" at the top of each required module and replaces references to `this` throughout the module (among other changes), even when the module resides in node_modules.
using `global: false` as a browserify option doesn't change that.

Here is the current entry point, only requiring jquery:

```
// app.js
'use strict';
var $ = require('jquery');
```

and the relevant part of the gulp task I am using:

```
var bundler = browserify(entryFile, {
  global: false
});

//bundler.add(require.resolve('babel-polyfill')); // uncommenting this line screws up jquery's code
bundler.transform(babelify, {
  presets: ['es2015']
});
```

Note that it doesn't matter _what_ is required through bundler.add(), I tried various modules (even jquery itself) with the same result. As long as something gets required this way, the code is modified to be in strict mode, which can break it if it's not ready for that.

